<DOC><DOCNO> AP880911-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-88 2317EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-TeacherStrikes     09-11 0231</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Teacher Strikes,0236</SECOND><HEAD>Strikes Cutting Into School Time In Six States</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   More than 100,000 students in six states were expected to haveclasses disrupted Monday by strikes involving more than 6,100teachers in 23 districts.   In Peabody, Mass., school officials and representatives of 400striking teachers were back at the bargaining table Sunday tryingto keep public school classes from being canceled a fourth day.   The state Labor Relations Commission has outlawed the strike,and school officials have mailed letters threatening to fire theteachers after a hearing procedure, said Mayor Peter Torigan.   A spokeswoman for the teachers dismissed the notices as apressure tactic and said the strike would continue.   Pay is at the heart of the Peabody dispute, and many of theothers in Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey, Ohio and Pennsylvania.   In Peabody, teachers are seeking a three-year contract with a 9percent pay increase each year. David Whitmore, a spokesman for thePeabody Federation of Teachers, said the town proposed a 5.5percent increase for each of the next three years.   The Peabody strike affects about 5,700 students. A strike inIllinois' Granite City district is disrupting classes for about8,200 students. Michigan and Pennsylvania each have strikes in 9districts, involving more than 40,000 students in each state.Strikes in Ohio affect about 4,250 students and in New Jersey about1,450 students.</TEXT></DOC>